    correctAnswer: "A",
    explanation: `The case scenario describes a girl with primary amenorrhea. Primary amenorrhea is defined as the absence of menses by the age of 15-16 years in the presence of normal growth and secondary sexual characteristics or by the age of 3-14 years in the absence of secondary sexual characteristics. According to this definition, this girl has primary amenorrhea and should be thoroughly investigated. Etiologies of primary amenorrhea are diverse but generally can be considered anatomical or hormonal. In a large case series of primary amenorrhea, the most common etiologies were: gonadal dysgenesis (including Turner syndrome) - 43%, Mullerian dysgenesis (absence of the vagina, sometimes with the absence of the uterus) - 15%, physiological delay of puberty (constitutional delay of puberty, chronic systemic disease, acute illness) - 14%, polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS) - 7%, isolated gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) deficiency - 5%, transverse vaginal septum - 3%, weight loss/anorexia nervosa/exercise-induced - 2%, hypopituitarism - 2%, and rare causes - <1%. A few points in the history can narrow down the diagnosis. Firstly, this girl has Tanner II breast development, indicating that she has been exposed to estrogen; however, at 16 years of age, more developed breasts with higher Tanner stages would be expected. Another point to consider is that this girl has no pubic or axillary hair. This finding can be either due to the arrested or delayed progression of puberty, which once has been started (as evident by breast buds), or incomplete androgen insensitivity, in which breast development occurs but the uterus and axillary and pubic hair are absent. The former is more likely for this girl, who is a professional ballet dancer with a BMI of 16. Low body weight, excessive physical exercise, and starvation are associated with hypogonadotropic hypogonadism (central hypogonadism). This is a very common finding among patients with anorexia nervosa or bulimia nervosa but is also seen in female athletes as a cause of primary or secondary amenorrhea. It could impede puberty from normal progression if it occurs before complete puberty. In hypogonadotropic hypogonadism, the characteristic finding is a decreased serum FSH (and LH). Since this patient has normal hormonal assays, ultrasonography should be performed for assessment of possible uterine anomalies or those of the genital tract, resulting in outflow obstruction, some of which include: Mullerian agenesis, transverse vaginal septum, Asherman's syndrome, and imperforated hymen. One interesting point in the question is that, in fact, with breasts at the Tanner II stage, ultrasound should have preceded the hormonal assays because, for instance, if this girl was found on ultrasound to have no uterus, there was no need to measure FSH and other hormones. The diagnostic pathway should then be continued with karyotyping (option E) and testosterone assays to investigate complete or incomplete androgen insensitivity as the most likely diagnosis. Referral to an adolescent health center (option B) may be indicated somewhere down the line once other causes of primary amenorrhea other than those related to excessive exercise, weight loss, and eating disorders are excluded with high certainty. It is not appropriate at this stage when other probable causes of primary amenorrhea are not yet fully investigated. This girl lags behind normal puberty and cannot be reassured (option C) unless the cause is ensured to be a constitutional delay of puberty. Interestingly and unlike the common belief, constitutional delay of puberty is not that common in females compared to males. Screening with a Pap smear (option D) starts at 25 and is not indicated for this girl now.`,
