    topic: "Obstetrics & Gynaecology",
    subtopic: "Primary amenorrhea - ovarian dysgenesis",
    stem: `A 16-year-old girl is brought to your GP clinic because her parents are concerned about her development. She has not started her menses yet, and according to her parents, she is the shortest of all her classmates at school. The breasts have not started budding on examination, but pubic and axillary hair growth is present. No abdominal mass, tenderness, or rebound tenderness is noted on examination. The remainder of the exam is unremarkable. The patient refuses a vaginal exam. Which one of the following can be the most likely diagnosis?`,
    options: [
      { label: "A", text: `Ovarian dysgenesis.` },
      { label: "B", text: `Mullerian agenesis.` },
      { label: "C", text: `Imperforated hymen.` },
      { label: "D", text: `A pituitary tumor.` },
      { label: "E", text: `Absent vagina.` },
    ],
    correctAnswer: "A",
    explanation: `Menses, the final piece of puberty, are expected by the age of 16. Failure to menstruate beyond this age is termed primary amenorrhea. Primary amenorrhea can be a feature of all the given options; however, short stature makes ovarian dysgenesis (e.g., Turner syndrome) the most likely diagnosis. Female puberty consists of three components: 1) Adrenarche – growth of pubic and axillary hair as a response to increased production of androgens by the zona reticularis layer of the adrenal gland; 2) Thelarche – breast development (the first sign of puberty in girls is breast budding); 3) Menarche – commencement of menses (the final event in puberty). In patients with ovarian dysgenesis, adrenarche often occurs around the expected time, like in a normal female. Still, thelarche and menarche are almost always delayed to various extents, depending on the underlying cause, because of decreased estrogen levels. Adequate estrogen levels are crucial to thelarche and menarche. Estrogen deficiency usually leads to short stature as a characteristic finding. In Mullerian agenesis (option B), imperforated hymen (option C), and absent vagina (option D), sexual development occurs normally because ovaries have full function. Still, there is no menstruation because of menstrual flow obstruction (e.g., imperforated hymen, absent vagina) or absent or abnormal menstruation (e.g., absent vagina). Many infiltrative diseases and tumors of the hypothalamus and pituitary (option E) can result in diminished GnRH release or gonadotropin destruction and, consequently, amenorrhea. Examples are craniopharyngioma, germinoma, and Langerhans cell histiocytosis. Such diseases, however, are often associated with other manifestations such as visual field defects and headaches, none of which are present in history.`,
    reference: "amc",
    difficulty: "hard",
