    correctAnswer: "B",
    explanation: `The ultrasound findings are suggestive of polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS), the most common cause of infertility due to anovulation. PCOS infertility is not absolute; many women conceive without treatment. For women with PCOS infertility, different treatment options are available: Non-pharmacological: If BMI>25 and age <35, intensive lifestyle program addressing weight loss (without pharmacological treatment for first 6 months) is recommended. Small weight loss (~5%) may restore menstrual cycle regularity and ovulation. Pharmacological: If pharmacological treatment is required, clomiphene citrate is the best first-line treatment with 30-50% pregnancy rate after six ovulatory cycles. In women with BMI <30-32 kg/m², metformin may have similar efficacy to clomiphene citrate and is first-line if concomitant impaired glucose tolerance. If clomiphene citrate, metformin, or combination is unsuccessful, gonadotropins are the next option. Laparoscopy with ovarian surgery/drilling (LOS) is an appropriate second-line treatment if clomiphene citrate with metformin has failed, with pregnancy rate as effective as 3-6 cycles of gonadotropin ovulation induction. IVF is recommended if all above are unsuccessful or if other contributing factors to infertility exist.`,
