    correctAnswer: "C",
    explanation: `Since the patient has been stable on carbamazepine, cessation or dose reduction is not wise. Carbamazepine is an enzyme-inducing antiepileptic drug that increases the metabolism of oral contraceptive pills, reducing their efficacy by 40-50%. This increases the risk of pill failure. With low-dose OCPs (microgynon 30), the failure rate would be 6%. Therefore, high-dose OCPs (microgynon 50) are recommended to minimize the risk of unplanned pregnancy. Even with high-dose OCPs, there is a small risk of unplanned pregnancy, and barrier methods can be considered along with microgynon 50 after discussion with the patient. Note: COCs, POPs, and Implanon® are affected by enzyme-inducing drugs. Mirena® and Depo Provera® are not affected and are often the best choice in such cases. Enzyme-inducing antiepileptic drugs include phenobarbital, primidone, phenytoin, carbamazepine, oxcarbazepine, and topiramate.`,
