    correctAnswer: "D",
    explanation: `Studies have shown that COCPs have different effects on cancers. COCPs cease ovulation and are associated with a decreased risk of ovarian cancer (option E) — women who have ever used COCPs have a 30-50% lower risk of ovarian cancer than women who have never used COCPs. This protective effect lasts up to 30 years after cessation. COCPs also decrease the risk of colorectal cancers (option B) by 15-20% due to reduced bile acids. Another cancer with decreased risk associated with COCP use is endometrial cancer (option A) — there is at least a 30% reduction in the risk of developing endometrial cancer in women who have ever used COCPs compared to those who have not. COCPs are associated with a slight increase in the risk of breast cancer (option C) compared to women who have never taken COCPs. The risk declines after cessation, and after ten years of cessation, will be the same as that of women who have never used COCs. However, COCPs are associated with an increased risk of cervical cancer (option D). Women who have used oral COCPs for five or more years have a higher risk of cervical cancer than women who have never used COCPs. The longer a woman uses COCPs, the greater the increase in her risk of cervical cancer will be. One study found a 10% increased risk for less than five years of use, a 60% increased risk with 5-9 years, and a doubling of the risk with ten or more years of use. This risk declines over time after cessation of COCPs. Such effect is probably due to changes in the susceptibility of cervical cells to persistent infection with high-risk HPV types, which are virtually the cause of all cervical cancers. Another hypothesis is that women on COCPs have more frequent unprotected sex, which increases the risk of HPV infection. In consulting Hanna, she should be told the main concern would be the increased risk of cervical cancer if COCPs are taken longer than five years as the main concern and the fact that there is a just slightly increased risk of breast cancer according to studies. COCPs would not be appropriate for her in the presence of any personal history of breast cancer, but even with breast cancer history in her first-degree relatives, she can still take COCPs. It should be explained to her that, in fact, OCPs decrease her risk of developing ovarian, endometrial, and colon cancers.`,
