    explanation: `Smoking more than 15 to 20 cigarettes a day in a woman older than 35 years is a contraindication to combined oral contraceptive pills. Progestogen-only preparations (e.g., progestogen-only pills) are options of choice when estrogen-containing preparations are contraindicated. The yearly failure rate is up to 10%, compared to 2 to 6% for combined pills. Male condoms are the next best appropriate option with a Pearl index of 3 compared to 0.5 of POPs. A diaphragm is a dome-shaped rubber cup with a flexible rim covering the cervix, creating a barrier to sperm, with a pregnancy rate of 6% in the first year and is not routinely used anymore in Australia. A cervical cap is slightly more rigid than a diaphragm, smaller in size, can be left in place for 48 hours, has a pregnancy rate over 9%, and is not a favorite and advisable method of contraception anymore.`,
