    correctAnswer: "B",
    explanation: `Candidiasis, also known as thrush, is due to a proliferation of vaginal yeasts. The majority of symptomatic infections are due to the proliferation of Candida albicans, but 10-20% of infections are due to a non-albicans species, such as C. glabrata or C. krusei. Contributing factors can predispose to candidiasis, such as antibiotic use, pregnancy, diabetes, and immune suppression, but in the majority of cases, no such factor can be identified. Candidiasis does not occur in a non-estrogenized vaginal environment, so it does not occur in prepubertal girls or postmenopausal women who are not on estrogen therapy. Occasionally, yeasts can be acquired from a sexual partner, but for the most part, candidiasis is due to the overgrowth of endogenous yeasts. Candidiasis clinically could present with vaginal discharge, vulval dermatitis, or both. Discharge is often described as white and curd-like but may be yellow or green due to an associated intense inflammatory infiltrate. Vulval dermatitis can result in itch, irritation, or soreness. Vulval skin can be red and edematous, with fissures and superficial erosions. Women may experience superficial dyspareunia and vulvar dysuria. Diagnosis is by microscopy and culture of the vaginal swab, which shows the presence of budding yeasts with or without pseudohyphae with a polymorphic inflammatory infiltrate, usually in the presence of lactobacilli and a low vaginal pH (<4.5). Cultures can be performed if microscopy is negative, but symptoms suggest candidiasis. Microscopy and culture can be negative with recent antifungal use and should be repeated if symptoms persist. Yeast is part of the commensal vaginal flora, and the presence of yeasts in the culture, in the absence of symptoms, does not require treatment. Recommended topical treatments include clotrimazole vaginal cream or pessary for 3-6 nights, 500mg pessary single dose, or miconazole vaginal cream or pessary for six nights. All topical and oral azole therapies give 80-90% cure rates. Topical treatments must be given per vagina (PV) to effect a cure. Longer duration treatment will be needed if symptoms are severe. With severe vulvitis, topical 1% hydrocortisone, with or without topical antifungal, is recommended. Nystatin is a polyene antifungal, less irritating than the azole class, but less potent. Oral nystatin (option A) is not absorbed and is ineffective. Nystatin vaginal cream can be used. Nystatin vaginal cream or pessaries, once daily for 14 days or twice daily for seven days, can be used for acute vaginal candidiasis but is not an option. Oral Fluconazole, 150mg single dose, repeated every 72 hours for 2 or 3 doses, can be used in non-pregnant women if symptoms are severe in cases of failed topical treatments in uncomplicated vulvovaginal candidiasis, for relapse prevention, and recurrent infections. Patients should be monitored, checking for tiredness, nausea, dark urine, pale feces, or jaundice. Liver function and serum potassium concentration should be measured at baseline and regular intervals, depending on the dose and duration of treatment. Fluconazole interacts with many medications. Women should be advised to stop fluconazole if they miss a period and exclude pregnancy before they take the next dose. Topical and systemic estrogens (HRT) (options C and D) can be used in post-menopausal symptoms but not as a treatment for candida. Topical clotrimazole can be a treatment option, but oral clotrimazole (option E) cannot.`,
