    explanation: `This scenario represents a case of primary amenorrhea as well as delayed puberty, evident by a complete lack of breast development and axillary and pubic hair. The most important step in the assessment of primary amenorrhea is always a thorough history and complete physical exam to check if secondary sexual characteristics are present. Breast development reflects estrogen exposure and is the best indicator that puberty has begun. In fact, the diagnostic approach to primary amenorrhea starts with breast assessment. Breasts at the Tanner III stage or higher are equivalent to the presence of secondary sexual characteristics (Tanner III or higher in females older than 13 years). With developing or developed breasts, the next thing to check is whether a normal uterus is present. This is achieved by a physical exam (if possible) and a pelvic ultrasound. With Tanner I breasts, secondary sexual characteristics are absent. In such cases, investigations start with measuring FSH either alone or with LH to assess the hypothalamus–pituitary–ovary (HPO) axis. This patient has not started breast development; therefore, the next step in management is measuring the FSH (and LH) for evaluation of HPO axis. TSH (option D) and prolactin are also routinely assessed as a part of a hormonal assay in delayed puberty. Exclusion of pregnancy should always be considered as well.`,
