    explanation: `Evidence suggests that combined oral contraceptive pills (COCs) have a small adverse effect on blood pressure, with an average increase of 8 mmHg for systolic and 6 mmHg for diastolic pressure. However, a minority of women may suffer severe hypertension induced by COCs. Unlike COCs, progestogen-only pills (POPs) do not appear to induce an increase in blood pressure; therefore, they are better options for hypertensive women. In women with well-controlled and monitored hypertension who are 35 years or younger, a trial of combined oral contraceptives may be appropriate as long as the patient is otherwise healthy, shows no signs of end-organ vascular disease, and does not smoke. If blood pressure remains well controlled several months after the trial is started, combination contraceptives may be continued. This woman seems to have hypertension. With the known effect of COCs on blood pressure, continuing the same pill without further action is incorrect. Adding a hypertensive medication while continuing the possible cause is not judicious unless there is severe hypertension or end-organ damage. While changing the contraception method seems reasonable, prescribing antihypertensives when other reversible causes of hypertension are addressed properly yet is not judicious. She is already on a low-dose estrogen preparation (20 mcg), and reducing the dose to the lowest dose available does not seem to help the issue.`,
