    explanation: `The clinical picture of a tense and tender uterus in the presence of vaginal bleeding is suggestive of placental abruption as the most likely diagnosis. The important clue is tachycardia and hypotension are disproportionate to the amount of vaginal bleeding, indicating that the bleeding is concealed. In concealed bleeding, blood accumulates between the placenta and the uterine wall. In the presence of hypotension and tachycardia, fluid resuscitation with intravenous isotonic fluids is the most appropriate next step in management. Blood typing and cross-matching should also be performed, and packed cells should be reserved in case of severe bleeding requiring blood transfusion. An ultrasound scan (option B) is then indicated to assess the placental and fetal status. Continuous CTG (option C) should be performed for fetal monitoring. Labour induction (option D) or caesarean section (option E) are indicated if there is maternal or fetal jeopardy.`,
